<subSubSection lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="34" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1588,2009]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1804,1829]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Description.</emphasis>
More than a dozen short erect branches (
<figureCitation box="[822,908,1804,1829]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1620,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 20. Niphates erecta Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864, a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9895 (scale bar = 1 cm), a 1, of RMNH Por. 9877 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of cross section of peripheral skeleton of RMNH Por. 9905, c – d, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeas, d, sigma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272971/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
a,a1) with irregular outline, up to about 
<quantity box="[1365,1436,1804,1828]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[219,307,1840,1864]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 cm</quantity>
in diameter. Color in alcohol red-brown. Flush or slightly raised oscules, 
<quantity box="[1190,1288,1840,1864]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
in diameter, scattered over the uneven punctate or irregularly conulose surface. Some branches have large numbers of zoanthids. Consistency firmly compressible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1588,2009]" lastBlockId="33.[151,1437,151,320]" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="34" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1948,1973]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[324,406,1948,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1620,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 20. Niphates erecta Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864, a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9895 (scale bar = 1 cm), a 1, of RMNH Por. 9877 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of cross section of peripheral skeleton of RMNH Por. 9905, c – d, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeas, d, sigma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272971/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
b) The ectosomal skeleton is an irregular three-dimensional reticulation of spongin-encased spicule tracts that form brushes fanning out over the surface, forming meshes of 200–300 µm diameter. The choanosomal reticulation is formed by thick spicule tracts, 90–120 µm in diameter (7–15 spicules in cross section) connected by thinner cross tracts, making irregular squarish meshes of 300–500 µm diameter. Many loose spicules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,151,320]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,223,248]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Spicules</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[318,404,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1620,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 20. Niphates erecta Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864, a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9895 (scale bar = 1 cm), a 1, of RMNH Por. 9877 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of cross section of peripheral skeleton of RMNH Por. 9905, c – d, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeas, d, sigma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272971/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs 20</figureCitation>
c–d) Oxeas and sigmas, the latter not found or rare in many specimens. Oxeas (
<figureCitation box="[236,319,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1620,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,373,1599]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 20. Niphates erecta Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864, a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9895 (scale bar = 1 cm), a 1, of RMNH Por. 9877 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of cross section of peripheral skeleton of RMNH Por. 9905, c – d, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeas, d, sigma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272971/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
c), robust, curved, length and thickness subject to considerable variation, 213– 
<emphasis box="[1191,1233,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">251</emphasis>
–288 
<date box="[1296,1330,261,284]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">x 7</date>
– 
<emphasis box="[1345,1394,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">13.1</emphasis>
–19 µm.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272971/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" targetBox="[151,1436,373,1599]" targetPageId="33">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1620,1703]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1620,1642]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">FIGURE 20</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864" authorityName="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti" authorityYear="1864" box="[300,814,1620,1642]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Niphates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="erecta">
<emphasis box="[300,462,1620,1642]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Niphates erecta</emphasis>
Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864
</taxonomicName>
, a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9895 (scale bar = 1 cm), a1, of RMNH Por. 9877 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of cross section of peripheral skeleton of RMNH Por. 9905, c–d, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeas, d, sigma.
